text: Well, it's the space certainly that I understand the best. That's where my background is. And that's why I've ended up here. But I think for the strategy that I'm really trying to pursue, to me, what makes commodities super interesting for an investor should be the ability to generate uncorrelated returns. You have a couple of dozen, if not more, different market structures, different groups of markets that are all not only uncorrelated with themselves, but uncorrelated a lot of the times with major asset classes. So equities and bonds and credit. It's a lot easier as a manager for me to try to deliver uncorrelated returns, I think, operating in an underlying landscape like that versus a long-term equity manager. It's just hard. That's very difficult. To try to deliver an uncorrelated return stream when your underlying assets that you're trading are all correlated. That's what offers it to me. I think the other big separator for commodities from other asset classes, I think, is around this notion that commodities are kind of instantaneously cash settled. They have a forcing function that mandates that prices converge to levels that the current market. Here and now is producing and consuming those assets. So equities, I always think of equities more as a perpetual security. There's really no maturity date when you own an equity tranche in something. And as such, you're kind of relying on the market to come around to your point of view, if you will, or to identify the fundamentals that you as a manager might have identified. On the commodity space, there's usually a finite time horizon here. Are we trading securities? Are we trading those securities? they're going to be consumed by somebody somewhere, or they're going to be stored or whatever is going to happen to them. And I think that it allows for a type of fundamental analysis that can play out over a very known time horizon. But if you're trading something with a six-month maturity, you don't have to guess, is the market going to figure this out in six months or not? You're either going to be right or you're going to be wrong. And then sort of pairing that with the derivatives market. It gives you a really robust landscape of opportunities to try to not only diversify across the different markets, but you can diversify through time, you can diversify through some of these other instruments. And I think that that is a fairly unique feature of the commodity space.
